node.text: Travel memories shape our personalities and stay with us for a lifetime. During the pandemic, we were unable to collect any new moments of this kind. However, neuroscientist Prof. Dr. Jäncke tells us about the importance of travel experiences for us. It's time: Let's make new memories. #MakeNewMemories

node.text: SWISS extends its award-winning culinary concept SWISS Saveurs to a majority of European flights from/to Zurich in SWISS Economy. From a menu that focuses on sustainable packaging and local producers like @confiseriespruengli, you can now order exactly what you want to eat or drink. But even if you’re not hungry, we’ve still got a complimentary treat for you. Find out more: https://bit.ly/3sz4YWw #flyswiss #SWISSsaveurs #SWISSelements

node.title: SWISS Saveurs – our new culinary concept

node.text:
Especially during the summer month the aircraft cabin can heat up quite quickly☀️ 
To prevent this the ground staff attaches a yellow tube as you can see on the picture in order to blow conditioned air inside the aircraft💨 
We could also use the APU (auxiliary power unit) to climatize the aircraft during ground time, but as the APU is consuming fuel the tube is the much better and „greener“ solution🍃

Have you already seen our post regarding sustainable fuel? If not, check it out⛽️

Have a great day
Felix👋

node.text:
Have you ever noticed that one pilot is always walking around the aircraft before each flight?

It is called the outside check.
Before every flight either the captain or the first officer has to do such a check👩‍✈️👨‍✈️
You walk around the aircraft and do a visual inspection to make sure that everything is alright✔️
Fore example no hydraulic leaks, no blocked pitot probes, no tire damage, etc.
Most of the time I enjoy doing this, but there are also days where I would rather stay inside the cockpit😉🌧

node.text:
Let‘s talk about weather☀️🌩🌧
Summer is finally here and so is the thunderstorm season⚡️
You can see our navigation display in this picture. 
The aircraft symbol represents our current position. With the help of our weather radar, we are able to detect areas of precipitation and its intensity. Those areas are displayed as green, yellow and red spots. Especially the red indications are often a sign of heavy precipitation, hail and up and down drafts. Pilots need to decide on the best way to circumnavigate those areas.
In this picture you can see that we are already deviating from our planned route (magenta line) and continue initially on a course of 030 degrees, which we have coordinated with the radar controller on the ground🗣
Swipe right to see how it looked like in real life and check out todays stories if you want to learn more about our decision making.

Felix👋

node.text:
During pilot training, the aerobatic training is one of the most exciting and fun flight lessons🙌
For about 8 hours in total we are getting trained by an aerobatic expert how do fly some advanced manoeuvres and recover the aircraft in difficult flight situations✈️

Felix

#flyswiss #flyswisscrew #training #upsetrecovery #verobeach #florida

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by flyswiss in Zürich Airport with @flyswiss. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
My office - one of the most advanced airliner cockpits🙌

Did you know that the captain (PIC - pilot in command) is always sitting on the left seat and the first officer always on the right?👩‍✈️👨‍✈️

However, the task distribution of who is flying the aircraft and who is monitoring the systems changes every flight.

Felix

#flyswiss #flyswisscrew #cockpit #a220 #airbus #office

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by flyswiss in Zürich Airport. May be an image of airplane and sky.

node.text:
Zurich Airport is a great place to spot aircraft📸
You can visit the observation deck and listen to the communication between the tower and the flight crews 🗣🎙 or you can go to the "Aussichtspunkt Flughafen", which is right in front of runway 14 and where I took this picture of our beautiful SWISS A220 seconds before touchdown🛬

#flyswiss #flyswisscrew #zurich #zrh #planespotting

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by flyswiss in Lufthansa Aviation Training Switzerland with @lufthansaaviationtraining. May be an image of helicopter and indoor.

node.text:
To keep our license valid and to be optimal prepared for every kind of irregularity or emergency situation we need to train in the full flight simulator every half a year for two days.

Those simulators are amazing. Inside a simulator is an exact copy of the real cockpit. Hyperrealistic motion, graphics and animations make you believe your are sitting in a real aircraft. 
And that is how it should be, as close to reality as possible to benefit the most from this training👨‍✈️👩‍✈️

Felix

#flyswiss #flyswisscrew #simulator #a220 #lat #lufthansaaviationtraining

node.text:
What a great welcome in Florence a few months ago. I had the pleasure of operating the first flight to Florence after the pandemic had started. The airport staff surprised us with a water salute and a huge poster „welcome back“. Swipe right to see the video...

#flyswiss #flyswisscrew #welcomeback #florence #FLR #crewfie
